File: Friends enjoying alcoholic beverages. Unsplash/Elevate JOHANNESBURG - The South African Liquor Brand owners Association wants SARS to defer nearly a billion rand in excise tax payments for alcohol industry participants. This follows the latest ban on sales late which kicked in on 28 June. The association, which represents major alcohol manufacturers, says the industry is facing a financial crisis. READ: SA Lockdown | SAB heads to court over liquor ban The industry estimates that the current two-week restriction will result in a loss of R6.1-billion in retail sales income. Meanwhile, government will lose an estimated R3.6-billion indirect tax revenue, excluding excise tax, for the two weeks. The deferment will also mean that the estimated loss in excise tax will be R1.5-billion.